Indonesia Stock Movers: Gas Negara, London Sumatra, Medco Energi

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-09-22T10:11:46Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-22/indonesia-stock-movers-gas-negara-london-sumatra-medco-energi.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  plunged 328.35 points, or 8.9
percent, to 3,369.14, the steepest drop since Oct. 8, 2008.  Energy companies: PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ),
the nation’s largest listed oil company, sank 12 percent to
2,150 rupiah, the most since Oct. 6, 2008. PT Energi Mega
Persada (ENRG IJ), the second-biggest, lost 11 percent to 149
rupiah, the lowest close since April 5.  Crude oil futures dropped as much as 3.8 percent to $82.63
a barrel in after-hours trading in  New York , extending
yesterday’s 1.2 percent slide. Investors speculated that fuel
demand will falter after the U.S. Federal Reserve said there are
“significant downside risks” to the economic outlook of the
world’s biggest crude-consuming nation.  Palm oil producers: PT Perusahaan Perkebunan London Sumatra
 Indonesia  (LSIP IJ), the nation’s third-largest listed
plantation company by market value, tumbled 11 percent to 1,920
rupiah, the biggest drop since October 2008. PT Bakrie Sumatera
Plantations (UNSP IJ) fell 13 percent to 310 rupiah.  Palm oil futures fell 1.7 percent to 3,013 ringgit ($955) a
metric ton in  Kuala Lumpur , a second day of losses.  PT Perusahaan Gas Negara (PGAS IJ), Indonesia’s biggest
distributor of the fuel, plunged 13 percent to 2,200 rupiah, the
lowest close since April 1, 2009. Bisnis Indonesia reported the
Indonesian government is reviewing the possibility of reducing
natural-gas sales to  Singapore  to secure supplies to the
domestic market. Gas Negara Corporate Secretary Sri Budi
Mayaningsih couldn’t be reached when called at her office.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
